B.TP=new A.dN("Inconsistent spacing and visual hierarchy across screens","Card padding, heading sizes, and label styles varied across the dashboard, making it harder to scan quickly \u2014 a significant issue for practitioners working under time pressure.",B.cG,"Nielsen H4: Consistency and Standards","Standardised spacing tokens and type scale applied across all screens in the second iteration.")
B.TO=new A.dN("Unclear copy on AI-enabled actions","Labels on AI-generated outputs did not make it obvious that the content was AI-produced, or that it required practitioner review before use.",B.cG,"Nielsen H1: Visibility of System Status","Explicit \u201cAI-generated \u2014 review before sending\u201d labels added to all AI outputs, with a distinct visual treatment separating them from practitioner-authored content.")
B.U_=new A.dN("Weak visual affordance on interactive elements","Several action buttons and session cards did not communicate their interactivity clearly, leading the usability participant to hesitate before interacting.",B.ds,"Nielsen H7: Flexibility and Efficiency / 2.4.7 Focus Visible","Hover and focus states added. Primary actions given stronger visual weight with filled button styles.")
B.U1=new A.dN("No system feedback after voice commands","The initial voice assistant prototype gave no visible feedback that a command had been received or understood, leaving practitioners uncertain whether to repeat themselves.",B.ds,"Nielsen H1: Visibility of System Status","A brief animated confirmation state added between command input and checklist generation, confirming the assistant had processed the instruction.")
B.Nz=s([B.TP,B.TO,B.U_,B.U1],t.jW)
B.U2=new A.v7(B.a7,B.Nz,"Accessibility and usability issues found","Issues surfaced during heuristic evaluation (Nielsen\u2019s ten heuristics) and addressed before practitioner testing.",null)
B.TR=new A.dN("No progress indicator in a five-screen flow","People had no way to gauge how far through onboarding they were or how much was left, which fed straight into the sense that the effort was open-ended.",B.cG,"2.4.8 Location","Added a step indicator to every onboarding screen, showing current position and total steps.")
B.TV=new A.dN("System permission dialogs appeared with no context","OS-level prompts for location and notifications arrived abruptly with no prior explanation. For anyone using a screen reader, the sudden modal shift was especially disorienting.",B.cG,"3.3.2 Labels or Instructions","Added a dedicated explainer screen before each OS prompt, with a plain-language reason and benefit for each permission requested.")
B.TU=new A.dN("Avatar selection wasn\u2019t usable with VoiceOver or TalkBack","The initial avatar grid used tap targets that were too small and had no accessible labels, making selection hard for anyone navigating by touch or screen reader.",B.cG,"2.5.5 Target Size / 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value","Increased avatar tap targets to a minimum of 48x48dp and gave each one a semantic label describing the breed or character.")
B.TW=new A.dN("Optional fields weren\u2019t labelled as optional","Photo upload and several profile fields were effectively optional but weren\u2019t marked as such, so people assumed they had to complete them to proceed.",B.ds,"3.3.2 Labels or Instructions","Labelled optional fields explicitly as \u201cOptional \u2014 you can add this later\u201d and added skip affordances where relevant.")
B.TY=new A.dN("The feature carousel had no pause or manual control","The carousel auto-advanced on a timer with no way to pause or step through it, which is a problem for anyone who needs more time to read.",B.ds,"2.2.2 Pause, Stop, Hide","Made the carousel manually navigated by default, with swipe and dot-tap controls, and removed the auto-advance.")
B.MS=s([B.TR,B.TV,B.TU,B.TW,B.TY],t.jW)
B.U3=new A.v7(B.aB,B.MS,"Accessibility considerations","Issues that came up during the heuristic review, fixed as part of the redesign rather than filed for later.",null)
B.U5=new A.v8(B.N,"Before","A single scrolling page that piled marketing preferences, assumptions and declarations, cover details and payment into one view, mostly as paragraphs of text. The information was technically all there, but it expected you to read the whole thing \u2014 and gave you little reason to trust the brand before asking you to commit.","After","A two-page flow. Page one leads with price and trust signals, then cover details, warranty questions and personal information. Page two handles assumptions and declarations \u2014 including an explicit, acknowledged call-out of the pre-existing conditions rules \u2014 before payment. All the FCA-mandated language is still there; it's just no longer cluttering the page and has been laid out so it's easier to consume.",null)
B.U6=new A.v8(B.aB,"Before","Five screens, sixteen questions, a mandatory photo upload, abrupt system permission prompts, and no explanation anywhere of what Perro actually offered. It asked for a lot and gave very little back before the first moment that might have made someone care.","After","Four screens and eleven questions, with the avatar system and optional photo, a feature carousel front-loading the value, a permissions explainer, and a subscription step that carries the same story through to the end. Setup stopped feeling like paperwork and started feeling like an introduction.",null)
B.p5=new A.dz(61298,"MaterialIcons",null,!1)
B.jS=new A.yD(1,"principle")
B.U8=new A.lB(B.N,"Through every layout decision there was one question I kept dragging things back to: does this make it easier for someone to understand what they're actually looking at? I cared about visual consistency and brand alignment too \u2014 but surfacing the right information at the right moment came first.","Design principle",B.p5,B.jS,null)
B.nm=new A.yD(0,"insight")
B.Ua=new A.lB(B.a7,"The sample of seven practitioners provided rich qualitative insight but limits generalisability. The low-contact workshop introduced delays and occasional ambiguity. The current output is at the prototype and concept-validation stage; future work would involve building an MVP integrated with real Google or Microsoft APIs, trialling it in practice with a small cohort, and adding quantitative usability measurement alongside the qualitative methods.","Limitations and future work",B.p5,B.nm,null)
B.I0=new A.dz(983357,"MaterialIcons",null,!1)
B.Ub=new A.lB(B.a7,"Design a practical, practitioner-centred tool that streamlines administrative tasks and supports mental health professionals before, during and after counselling sessions \u2014 without compromising the therapeutic relationship or introducing ethical risk.","Research aim",B.I0,B.jS,null)
B.HX=new A.dz(62329,"MaterialIcons",null,!1)
B.Ef=new A.yD(2,"warning")
B.Uc=new A.lB(B.a7,"Using RRI prompts and Moral IT cards, I mapped all stakeholders and systematically interrogated data flows, consent boundaries, and AI usage risks. Key outcomes: AI limited to non-diagnostic roles only (summarisation, scheduling prompts); per-client AI toggles required; on-device or privacy-preserving architectures favoured; explicit practitioner approval required before any client-facing action.","RRI ethical review",B.HX,B.Ef,null)
B.I1=new A.dz(984664,"MaterialIcons",null,!1)
B.Ud=new A.lB(B.aB,"Three ideas shaped more or less every decision I made. Shorten and refocus onboarding around what actually improves the first session rather than what\u2019s nice to have on file. Lead with value before asking for anything. And go after the specific friction points the research had surfaced, namely the photo upload, the unexplained permissions and the late-funnel fatigue, rather than redesigning for the sake of it.","Strategy",B.I1,B.jS,null)
B.nz=new A.o(1,0.6078431372549019,0.4980392156862745,0.8313725490196079,B.e)
B.Ue=new A.v9("Perro \u2014 Case study 02",B.nz,"Perro onboarding and subscription redesign","Perro had a genuinely strong product. You could track your dog\u2019s activity, work through enrichment and training content, set things up so the whole household could collaborate, and earn up to \xa3500 of Woof benefits over time. The people who got past the first session tended to like it, which was rather the problem, because a large share of new users never got that far. They were leaving during onboarding, very often before they\u2019d reached anything that showed them what Perro could actually do for them. Would you stick around for a setup flow that asks a lot and hands back nothing first? Most people didn\u2019t, and that was costing real subscriptions.","I had two weeks, part-time, and a tight set of constraints: Flutter only, no backend changes, and nothing that broke the experience for existing users. Rather than redesign on a hunch, I started from the Mixpanel funnels, watched usability sessions to understand the why behind each drop-off, and then redesigned the onboarding and subscription flow and built it directly in Flutter, since I was the developer too. It reduced drop-off, lifted completion, and increased subscription conversion, and the work was later cited as one of the product\u2019s strengths when the company was acquired.",null)
B.Uf=new A.v9("Perfect Pet Insurance \u2014 Case study 01",B.jW,"Pet insurance checkout page redesign","Insuring your pet is an emotional exercise. You hand over a fair bit of money every month hoping the insurer takes the financial \u2014 and mental \u2014 stress off your hands when your pet isn't at its best. So when you've never heard of a brand and the first thing it shows you is a wall of policy text, would you buy? I probably wouldn't. This is what customers were faced with when they landed on Perfect Pet's 'Review Quote' page: they'd come through aggregators like Compare the Market and Money Super Market, and were met with the exact same wall of text. Given that aggregators are our main source of sales, getting this right could make a genuine difference for customers as well as the business.","I was allocated one sprint - 2 weeks. I went in thinking it was a tidy-up job \u2014 make a dated page look like it belonged in the modern world, no copy changes. I decided to begin with a competitor review, went through Hotjar recordings of the existing page, came up with a redesign and then sat down with eleven colleagues from claims, complaints, finance and renewals for testing. Recruiting internally was a time-crunch call, and yes, conventional wisdom states that people who deal with pet insurance all day make poor stand-in users, but halfway through the first interview, I realised I should go down a different angle. It was obvious they knew exactly what happens when this page doesn't do its job \u2014 and the interviews quietly turned a visual refresh into something more interesting.",null)
B.o_=new A.o(1,0.23921568627450981,0.7490196078431373,0.6588235294117647,B.e)
B.Ug=new A.v9("MSc Dissertation \u2014 Case study 03",B.o_,"Crafting Counselling Companions","Mental health practitioners spend 15\u201320 minutes of every session on admin. This project asked what a tool built specifically for them could do about it.","My MSc dissertation in Human\u2013Computer Interaction at Newcastle University combined semi-structured interviews with seven practitioners, a low-contact co-design workshop, iterative Figma prototyping, and an RRI ethical review \u2014 producing a validated concept for a practitioner-centred practice dashboard and voice assistant.",null)
B.bj=new A.zl("Positive",0,"positive")
B.Uv=new A.d7("Pre-existing conditions got their own page with an explicit tick-box","All eleven raised it unprompted. A checkbox buried in an assumptions section was never going to fix a misunderstanding this fundamental.","Stanley from Finance summed it up: \"Having it as its own page \u2014 we're not hiding it. It's quite helpful.\" Kerry noted it changes the claims conversation, since customers have declared from the outset.",B.bj)
B.Ut=new A.d7("Excess moved to page one","It was missing entirely, which was both a clarity gap and a missed marketing opportunity given it's one of the lowest excesses in the market.","Now visible alongside cover details, presented as a feature rather than a buried disclosure.",B.bj)
B.kk=new A.zl("Trade-off",2,"tradeoff")
B.Uj=new A.d7("A qualifier was added to the lifetime cover headline","The unconditional wording sets an expectation the policy can't always keep, and pre-existing exclusions are the most common reason a claim is declined.",'Something like "subject to your pet\'s health history" keeps it accurate without changing the meaning for most customers. Flagged to copy and compliance.',B.kk)
B.Ur=new A.d7("Interactive components were standardised","The audit found four button styles and three expansion-panel treatments across the flow \u2014 enough inconsistency to make the page feel unconsidered, which doesn't help when you're trying to earn trust.","One token set across buttons, tooltips, modals and toggles. Engineering noted it'd cut maintenance overhead too, with all components being standardised at the time of writing.",B.bj)
B.Us=new A.d7("Mobile was deferred to a follow-up sprint","A full responsive overhaul wasn't realistic in two weeks within MudBlazor's grid, though the designs exist for when development catches up. Mobile is ~35% of traffic but most completions still happen on desktop.","Backlogged, to be picked up once the A/B experiment gives us something to work with.",B.kk)
B.Mv=s([B.Uv,B.Ut,B.Uj,B.Ur,B.Us],t.qv)
B.UA=new A.qE(B.N,B.Mv,"Key decisions","The calls that shaped the redesign, what drove them, and what we saw.",null)
B.Up=new A.d7("AI features made opt-in on a per-client basis, not globally","Practitioners had strong and varied views on AI in clinical contexts. A single on/off toggle felt too blunt; per-client control let each practitioner calibrate based on their own clinical judgement and the nature of each therapeutic relationship.","Usability session participant responded positively to the granularity. The toggle became a visible signal of practitioner agency, not just a compliance checkbox.",B.bj)
B.Uz=new A.d7("Voice assistant outputs shown as editable checklists before execution","Early thinking around voice-first interfaces assumed direct execution would feel faster. Research made clear that practitioners need to see and approve what the system intends to do before it acts \u2014 especially for anything client-facing.","The checklist model removed the core fear of automated errors in clinical communication. Participants described it as the feature that made the voice assistant feel trustworthy rather than risky.",B.bj)
B.oe=new A.zl("Neutral",1,"neutral")
B.Uq=new A.d7("Low-contact asynchronous co-design workshop format instead of synchronous sessions","Mental health practitioners have almost no availability for time-intensive research participation. A one-week asynchronous format using Google Workspace tools they already knew lowered the barrier significantly.","Higher participation rate than anticipated. Some delay and occasional confusion about instructions, suggesting that a short synchronous briefing call at the start would improve a future iteration.",B.oe)
B.Ui=new A.d7("Focused on practitioner back-office tools, not patient-facing features","Patient-facing mental health apps are a crowded and ethically complex space. Practitioner tools are underrepresented in both the market and in HCI research. The scope decision was both strategic and principled.","Kept the research focused and gave the design a clearer value proposition. The practitioner-as-primary-user framing also produced sharper, more actionable findings than a broader scope would have allowed.",B.bj)
B.M9=s([B.Up,B.Uz,B.Uq,B.Ui],t.qv)
B.UB=new A.qE(B.a7,B.M9,"Key design decisions","Decisions shaped by the tension between capability and trust in a sensitive, high-stakes context.",null)
B.Ux=new A.d7("Took pet illnesses and detailed health information out of onboarding entirely","These fields sat early, added real perceived effort, and offered nothing back in the first session. People weren\u2019t invested enough yet to feel it was a fair trade.","A major resistance point disappeared. The information moved to a later in-app prompt, where people had the context and the motivation to give it.",B.bj)
B.Uk=new A.d7("Led with a feature carousel before the first form screen","Both the competitive analysis and the sessions pointed at the same gap \u2014 people had no idea what Perro would do for them before being asked to hand over information.","Tested against a minimal version without it. The carousel did better on engagement and downstream completion, and became the production baseline.",B.bj)
B.Um=new A.d7("Replaced mandatory photo upload with an avatar system and optional image","Sessions showed this was a silent exit trigger. People left to find a suitable photo and frequently didn\u2019t come back, so making it optional removed a low-value blocker.","Drop-off at the dog profile step fell noticeably after launch, and people could finish setup in one sitting without leaving the app.",B.bj)
B.Uu=new A.d7("Added a plain-language permissions explainer before the OS prompts","Abrupt system dialogs for location and notifications appeared out of nowhere. Most people either dismissed them or felt ambushed.","Acceptance improved. People who read the explainer were far more likely to grant both location and notification access.",B.bj)
B.Un=new A.d7("Echoed the carousel benefits on the subscription screen","The paywall used to feel disconnected from the onboarding story. Repeating the same four benefit areas tied it back in.","Subscription conversion rose and more people chose longer-term plans. Feedback described the step as feeling \u201cfairer\u201d and \u201cmore honest\u201d.",B.bj)
B.Uy=new A.d7("Moved activity level and some fitness questions to post-signup prompts","They were arriving when people were already fatigued, and before they\u2019d done anything in the app that made the questions feel relevant.","Late-funnel fatigue dropped. The information still gets collected, just at a point where people have a reason to care about it.",B.bj)
B.J0=s([B.Ux,B.Uk,B.Um,B.Uu,B.Un,B.Uy],t.qv)
